article.description: Shane Battier silenced Peja  Stojakovic in the fourth quarter and made a little noise of his own.
article.headline: Stojakovic held to one 4th-quarter point
article.linkText: Shane on you! Battier sparks Grizz past Kings
article.story: MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Shane Battier didn't do much over the first three quarters. In the fourth, he did plenty at both ends. Battier keyed a fourth-quarter rally with 11 points to help the Memphis Grizzlies defeat Sacramento 105-100 Tuesday night. Six Memphis players scored in double figures as the Grizzlies snapped Sacramento's four-game winning streak and beat the Kings for the first time since November, 2001, a string of eight games. It was a franchise-record fifth consecutive home win for Memphis. "We were finally able to limit them on the defensive end to one shot, and the shots they did get we contested," said Battier, who finished with 13 points. The teams were tied at 83 with just under eight minutes left before Memphis went on a 7-1 run for a 90-84 lead with 5:15 remaining. Sacramento got within 94-93 on a drive by Brad Miller with 3:15 remaining, but never any closer. "(Memphis) got some calls, and we didn't," Miller said. "On the road, you don't get some of those calls. It happens sometimes. We have to find a way to win the games when we don't get those calls." Pau Gasol scored 22, James Posey had 16 points, and Earl Watson, Stromile Swift and Bonzi Wells scored 11 each. Swift added 10 rebounds and Watson handed out 13 assists. Battier, who hit three of his four shots in the fourth, had four of the Grizzlies' 10 blocked shots. "I didn't get many looks in the first half, so I was a little stiff," said Battier, who was 0-for-4 entering the fourth. "Once I hit some free throws and saw the ball go in the basket, it brought my confidence back." Peja Stojakovic led Sacramento with 27 points, while Miller finished with 20 points and 16 rebounds. Bobby Jackson had 13 off the bench, and Mike Bibby finished with 12 while shooting just 2-of-14. Sacramento, thanks to Stojakovic's 18 first-half points, led 51-49 at the break. Stojakovic had 14 in the first quarter and hit his first six shots as Sacramento shot 65 percent to open the game. Gasol led a Grizzlies comeback, eventually resulting in a Memphis lead with just over three minutes remaining before the break. Gasol had 16 in the half. There were times in the game when the Memphis forward, who has been criticized for not playing tough inside, muscled his way for baskets and fouls against the Kings' physical front line. "I had to come out really hard," Gasol said. "They're a very talented and physical team and very hard to defend. You've got to go at them and really take it to them." Memphis made a run in the third and led 68-63, but poor shooting and a flurry of turnovers contributed to a 15-2 run that helped the Kings take a 78-76 lead into the fourth. Still, the Kings, who were 15-2 for the season when leading after three quarters, weren't able to put away the Grizzlies. "We didn't do anything that we wanted to do," Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. "We gave them too many chances. They beat us to loose balls. I am surprised that we were in the game." Game Notes: Memphis PG Jason Williams missed his ninth game because of a strained upper back. ... Before the game and at halftime, the New Orleans Bowl featuring the University of Memphis Tigers against North Texas State was shown on the scoreboard above the court. Score updates were given at various times. ...The Kings lineup of Stojakovic, Miller, Doug Christie, Bibby and Vlade Divac has started all 22 of Sacramento's games. ...Memphis G Mike Miller left the game after twisting his ankle with about nine minutes left in the second quarter. He returned at the start of the second half. ...Watson recorded the first double-double of his career, while Swift had his first of the season. Brad Miller had his 10th of the season.
